What is this analysis?

This notebook is for selecting a game and identifying its most comparable games using data from boardgamegeek.com. I use a dimension reduction method (PCA) to understand the main points of variation in data from boardgamegeek. I then compute the Euclidean distance between all games using based on their values on the first ten principal components.

Games with the shortest distances between them have similar data - games that are close to each otehr can be thought of as neighbors. This document identifies a game’s nearest neighbors and illustrate some of the dimensions that make the games similar.

Most Similar Games to Tindaya

The table below displays the most similar games to Tindaya using data from boardgamegeek (BGG). The reported similarity score is the (squared) inverse of the Euclidean distance between two games.

Note: The analysis does not make use of a game’s number of ratings, average, or geek average, but instead looks only at a game’s categories, mechanics, playing time, player count, and complexity. The current approach for computing the Euclidean distance weighs each component equally; I plan to explore a change to this in the future by using a different measure of distance, as we would reasonably expect some components to be more important than others.

Examining PCA Variable Loadings

What explains a game’s score on each principal component?

To gain a better understanding of these principal components, we can look at the loadings for the variables in the dataset. These are the the contributions of each variable to the ten components used in computing the distance between games. Large loadings (either positive or negative) for a variable indicate that there is a strong relationship between that variable and the component.

For instance, on the first principal component (PC1), time per player, average weight, and playing time have the highest positive loadings, while party game and max players have negative loadings. This indicates that this component seems to map to a game’s complexity - longer, more complex games will have high positive scores on this component while simpler, shorter, party games with lots of players will have low scores.
